The Data Science Pipeline¶

In this tutorial, we are going to learn the steps of the data pipeline by asking the question - Which groups of people are most affected by shootings? The steps of this tutorial's data pipeline will include:

¶

Data collection/curation + parsing (if necessary
Data management and representation
Exploratory data analysis
Hypothesis testing and machine learning
The communication of insights attained

Specifically, we will be analyzing a dataset recording shooting incident data in New York from 2016 to 2020.

Which groups of people are most affected by shootings?¶

Introduction¶

Firearm related violence and has become a prevalent topic in conversations in the United States especially surrounding gun control. However, there is an extremely important aspect that is less acknowledged: who are the groups of people that tend to be victims? For example, the prominence of school shooting discussion makes any student feel more uneasy than someone who is not. Are there certain groups of people that are more affected than others? This would provide valuable insight into understanding where solution efforts need to be focused. As government and various nonprofit organizations work to deal with these issues, it is crucial to learn where resources need to be concentrated in bettering education, mental health support, and efforts of protection. If there is any identifiable trend, among location/age/etc., it might also have the capablility to demonstrate what is actually happening and show where resources must be focused.

Data is found at https://data.cityofnewyork.us/Public-Safety/NYPD-Shooting-Incident-Data-Historic-/833y-fsy8 found through https://catalog.data.gov/

Data collection/curation + parsing (if necessary)¶

The first step is data collection/curation + parsing. This step is primarily focused on locating where the data is and putting it in an accessible location. A website? A file? and then subsequently finding the steps to properly get the data in order to achieve this. This can be done in numerous ways such as using a website/database/source's API, using a module to access elements, or using a downloadable file.

Let's explore data collection/curation.

The takeaway is that Python has many tools available and datasets often have downloadable files for collecting the data, so take time in exploring what is available as well as don't. be afraid to try things and see what happens, yet remember to validate the data is accurate. For this specific dataset, webscraping wasn't the best method but if your dataset requires webscraping, a useful tool too be aware of is BeautifulSoup. It has capabilities for taking content from the webpage, changing the data's format and much more.

Data management/representation¶

Data management and representation is handling where the data is stored and what elements are useful from it. If there are values that do not make sense, it is really important to learn what they are as they might be important to answering your question. Data structures are very important in Data Representation because they guide you by limiting the number of appropriate operations. This aids in preventing analysis on unmeaningful/invalid data. The data structure used in this scenario will be a dataframe. Dataframes are extremely useful but there are other data structures out there that might be more appropriate for representing a data set. Structures like dictionaries, lists, numpy arrays (ndarray), and so on are out there. But don't worry if not all of these memorized since tons of documentation is present online if you're unsure.

For example, we can check out numpy arrays here: https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.ndarray.html

Let's observe the dataframe in action to see how exactly we are representing our data.

IMPORTANT!¶

Notice the NaN values in the LOCATION_DESC column? Everytime a dataset is going to be analyzed we have to acknowledge those missing values and factor it into our analysis. The missing data can be identified as missing at random (MAR), missing at completely random (MCR) or missing not at random (MNAR). For the purposes of the dataset I am analyzing today, I am classifying any missing data as MCAR because of the connotation the variables that are missing have and the lack of reasons there would be for it to be MAR or MNAR.

Even though the true reason might actually be something else, it is the best practice in data science to state why you are classifying it that way and to factor it in for those who see/hear the analysis. Missing data is actually a very common occurence so it is not an option to ignore it without high risk of misunderstanding or disregarding what could be valuable information.

Exploratory data analysis¶

Exploratory analysis is exploring, learning, and summarizing the data to give any information about what the data may be saying.

Data visualization (such as graphical representation of data) is a powerful tool to help really understand what is happening. Not only do visual elements provide a more appealing view of the data, but they also give understanding in cases where it is difficult otherwise. Extremely large and unsorted datasets placed on a plot can make their patterns significantly more recognizable. Although every dataset is going to be slightly different in which representations most accurately portay the data and show what is occuring, it will often be extremely helpful in giving a clearer view of the data.

Let's examine where the shootings are happening mostly to see if there is a specific location we should pay attention to.

Interestingly, the same groups that are most likely victims also are shown as perpetrators. How might this happen?

An important aspect of any data science is contextualizing the data that is being worked with.

Violence, in general is frequently cyclic in nature, being passed from previous abuse - we also have to acknowledge the disparities in communities that have been present through the years.

Hypothesis testing and machine learning¶

Analysis/Hypothesis testing and ML is essentially saying, we have this idea on how these two components of the data are related - now how are we gonna test it?

We will see what this would like for this specific dataset but first let's understand a bit more of what these terms mean.

  • Hypothesis testing is testing a given hypothesis by comparing it with the null hypothesis. What exactly is a null hypothesis? The null hypothesis is a default hypothesis in which the relationship and statistical significance between two items is measured to be zero.
  • A null hypothesis here would be that factors like location, age, race, sex, gender, and so on do not play a role in being a victim.

My hypothesis is that they do, due to the history of gender bias/inequality, history of racial minority communities being underfunded by the government, age being a factor in accessibility to weaponry. The graphs shown so far demonstrate this to an extent as well. For location, I am hypothesizing that the high numbers of incidents of some areas are simply a result of more people in the area due to the variation in the graphs shown in the visualization overtime.

Let's begin with a null hypothesis that gender and being a victim have no correlation and see what we can find out.

Communication of insights attained¶

It can not go without saying that this step in the data science pipeline is the most critical component. If all the other steps are correctly executed, and what the data shows isn't properly explained then it is useless. In order to be able to correctly execute this step, we need to be communicating what we have done and why. There isn’t a point in doing data science if it doesn’t result in changes or knowledge being learned from it.

So what is the data communicating?

The data shows how victims of NYC shooting violence are disproportionally black males who are around the age of 24-44, we can see how gender plays a role in if you are more likely to be a perpetrator, and how location isn't a factor with these specific locations.

What does this mean and why does it matter?

This demonstrates a need for implementing policies and funding mental health support, education, and protection of the areas of these people. By recognizing how violence affects the communities where they live, the data presents a reality that is very unfortunate and can not be ignored. This data specifically observes NYC, but we can the disproportionate affects of women being affected and black men being affected. According to census.gov, in 2019 only approximately 24% of residents in NYC were black while only 3% were mixed. (Source: https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/newyorkcitynewyork). According to censusreporter.org, about 15% of the population in NYC is in the age range 20-29. https://censusreporter.org/profiles/16000US3651000-new-york-ny/. Understanding the population before making final assumptions is extremely important. If the largest percentage of people living in an area were often victims it would seem that it is a result of the population and not any other factors. But since we can observe these groups are not actually the majority, we can have more confidence in understanding why resources need to be dedicated to providing resources and accessibility to members of these groups so that the cycle of violence can be broken. Whether violence occurs among these groups as a result of lack of investment of the government, preconceived notions, or inaccessibility to previous resources, it is clear that policy needs to be put into action to help these groups so they are no longer victims of violence.
